article.description: Jennifer Gillom had 17 points, seven rebounds and four assists to lead the Phoenix Mercury to a 78-63 victory over the Sacramento Monarchs on Tuesday night.
article.headline: Mercury inflict much damage from foul line
article.linkText: Mercury keep losses piling up on Monarchs
article.story:
PHOENIX (AP) -- On a poor shooting night, Sacramento stayed close
to Phoenix for 29 minutes. But fouls ended up being the difference
by the end.

	   Jennifer Gillom had 17 points, seven rebounds and four assists
to lead the Phoenix Mercury to a 78-63 victory over the Sacramento
Monarchs on Tuesday night.

	   Gillom had 11 points in the second half when Phoenix (5-2)
pulled away.

	   "We are back to the team we were from the beginning,'' Gillom
said. "This is the team I like, because we fight hard and play
hard.''

	   Sacramento (1-6), a Western Conference finalist last year, has
been without leading scorer Yolanda Griffith and regular Edna
Campbell for most of the season.

	   The Monarchs could have used them Tuesday, as neither team led
by more than five points until the final eight minutes.

	   Phoenix then went on an 18-5 run to go up 66-53 with 5:55 left.

	   The Mercury also made 32 of 36 free throws on the night to
14-of-15 for Sacramento.

	   The Monarchs committed 26 fouls to Phoenix's 15.

	   "I thought we just fouled them too much,'' Sacramento coach
Maura McHugh said. "This is too good a team to let them go to the
line that much.''

	   In her second game running the team in place of Cynthia Cooper,
Mercury assistant coach Linda Sharp said, "Anytime you get to the
free throw line 36 times, it makes a difference.''

	   Cooper remained in Houston on Tuesday after a surrogate mother
gave birth to Cooper's twins Saturday.

	   Sharp is 1-1 as acting coach. Phoenix plays at Houston on
Friday.

	   Kedra Holland-Corn had 19 points to lead the Monarchs.

	   The Mercury made 13 of their final 14 free throws to hold off
Sacramento, which missed 13 of its last 16 field goal attempts, all
in the final six minutes.

	   "They shot a lot of free throws,'' Sacramento's Ruthie Bolton
said. "We should have never been in that position. Down the
stretch we had the momentum. It was our fault and we just didn't
get a break.''

	   Holland-Corn made two free throws and a 3-pointer and Ticha
Penicheiro added another 3-pointer to get Sacramento to within
66-61 with 4:49 left but it never got closer.

	   Gordana Grubin added 16 points for Phoenix. La'Keshia Frett had
14 points for Sacramento, while Tangela Smith added 11 and Bolton
10.

	   Phoenix, which finished with a 34-26 rebound advantage, shot 40
percent (21-of-53) from the field, while Sacramento was 23-of-67
(34 percent).

	   Adriana Moises hit her third 3-pointer with 13:42 left to give
Phoenix the lead for good and then Sacramento went cold, missing 18
of 23 shots from the field the rest of the way.
